Nike Popoola Anchor Insurance Company Limited has said it paid N957m claims to its policyholders in the first 10 months of 2020. It said this in a statement on Tuesday entitled ‘Anchor pays N957m claims in 10 months’. The company’s Managing Director, Mr Ebose Augustine, said, “Meeting customers’ genuine claims requests and doing so within a specified time limit have been parts of the practices. “Anchor Insurance was known for and we take unrepentant pride in meeting our promise of putting smiles back on the faces of our policyholders whenever the risk insured against crystallises.” Giving a breakdown of the claims paid, Ebose said N204.3m was paid to affected customers under the oil and gas class, general accident was N197.5m, motor insurance was N197.4m, loss of employment insurance scheme was N108.6m, while N89.1m was paid to those affected under the engineering class. He said others included marine insurance where affected claimants received N63.2m, fire class had N33.1m and bonds had N27.7m respectively. He that COVID-19 pandemic affected businesses and lives which gave rise to high cases of claims demands on insurers. The managing director said, “We at Anchor Insurance had our own fair share of the claims report, especially the loss of employment insurance scheme, but we were equal to the task as the primary duty of any insurance company was to pay claims.” Copyright PUNCH.
